## Vaathiyaar's Sorted Bookshelf

Vaathiyaar arranges books on a shelf. "Every book on the left has a smaller number. Every book on the right has a bigger one. Finding any book takes just log(n) steps!"

### BST Property
- Left child < Parent < Right child
- This holds for **every** node in the tree
- Inorder traversal gives **sorted** output

### BST Operations

```python
class BST:
    def __init__(self):
        self.root = None

    def insert(self, val):
        self.root = self._insert(self.root, val)

    def _insert(self, node, val):
        if not node:
            return TreeNode(val)
        if val < node.val:
            node.left = self._insert(node.left, val)
        elif val > node.val:
            node.right = self._insert(node.right, val)
        return node

    def search(self, val):
        return self._search(self.root, val)

    def _search(self, node, val):
        if not node:
            return False
        if val == node.val:
            return True
        elif val < node.val:
            return self._search(node.left, val)
        else:
            return self._search(node.right, val)
```

### Complexity

| Operation | Average | Worst (skewed) |
|-----------|---------|----------------|
| Search | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Insert | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Delete | O(log n) | O(n) |

> **Key Concept:** A BST degrades to O(n) when unbalanced (inserting sorted data). Self-balancing trees (AVL, Red-Black) fix this.

